Summary statistics and law of large numbers

Introduction to summary statistics and to the Law of large number

What will we learn in this empirical example ?

  1. Importing data in Python.
  2. Computing averages and summary statistics.
  3. Applying the law of large numbers for estimating a covariance matrix.
  4. Finding the portfolio with the smallest variance.

Theory behind the empirical exercise

In this short document, we show how to compute the weights of the financial portfolio exhibiting the smallest variance. Assuming that we have a universe of N asset returns X=(X1,...,XN)′X=(X1,...,XN)′. We want to choose the portfolio that exhibits the smallest variance in this universe. As a reminder, the optimal portfolio solves the following optimization program

ω̂ =argminωw′Σw  such that ∑i=1Nωi=1,ω^=argminωw′Σw  such that ∑i=1Nωi=1,
in which Σ=V(X)Σ=V(X), i.e. the covariance matrix of the asset returns. To do so, we need an estimate of the covariance matrix ΣΣ. Denoting xt=(xt,1,...,xt,N)′xt=(xt,1,...,xt,N)′, the N asset returns observed at time tt, the law of large numbers tells us that
Σ≈1T∑t=1T(xt−x¯)(xt−x¯)′Σ≈1T∑t=1T(xt−x¯)(xt−x¯)′
 in which x¯=1T∑Tt=1xtx¯=1T∑t=1Txt.

From theory to practice

Summary statistics

We can have a closer look to the asset returns. First, we focus on one asset and look at the different quantiles of the series. The R function summary provides the 25%, 50% (Median) and 75% quantiles as well as the min and the max of the series. We observe that the IBM asset returns are between -5.9% and 4.9% over this period.

def summary(y):
    y = np.array(y,ndmin=2)
    K = np.size(y,0)
    nobs = np.size(y,1)
    quant = np.linspace(25,100,4)/100
    Stats = np.zeros([K,6])
    for i in range(0,K):
        Stats[i,0] = np.min(y[i,:])
        quantile = np.quantile(ret_IBM,quant)
        Stats[i,[1,2,4,5]] = quantile
        Stats[i,3] = np.mean(y[i,:])
        
    df=pd.DataFrame(Stats,columns=["Min.","1st. Qu.","Median","Mean","3rd Quar.","Max."])
    return(df)
    
print(summary(ret_IBM))
##        Min.  1st. Qu.    Median      Mean  3rd Quar.     Max.

Creating its own summary statistics

We now build a function that will compute important summary statisitics such as the mean, the standard deviation, the skewness and the excess kurtosis.

def mystats(y):
    y = np.array(y,ndmin=2)
    K = np.size(y,0)
    nobs = np.size(y,1)
    Stats = np.zeros([K,5])
    for i in range(0,K):
        mean = np.mean(y[i,:])
        std = np.std(y[i,:])
        Stats[i,0] = np.size(y,1)
        Stats[i,1] = mean
        Stats[i,2] = std
        Stats[i,3] = (np.sum((y[i,:]-mean)**3)/std**3)/nobs
        Stats[i,4] = (np.sum((y[i,:]-mean)**4)/std**4)/nobs - 3
        df=pd.DataFrame(Stats,columns=["Obs","Mean","St dev.","Skewness","Ex. Kurtosis"])
    return(df)

Calling mystats for IBM or for two other returns gives the following results:

Let us compare the IBM returns with a Normal distribution. We have studied an unbiased estimate of the expectation and of the variance. As other estimators, we can also invoke the law of large Numbers (LLN) and use a biased but consistent estimator for the variance. Using one of these estimators for the expectation and the variance, we can compare our series with draws sampled from a Normal distribution with moments equal to the IBM expectation and variance.

# Fit a normal distribution to the data:
mu_std = norm.fit(ret_IBM)
# Plot the histogram.
sns.distplot(np.transpose(ret_IBM), hist=True, kde=True, 
             bins=int(180/5), color = 'darkblue', 
             hist_kws={'edgecolor':'black'},
             kde_kws={'linewidth': 4})
#plt.hist(np.transpose(ret_IBM), bins=100, color='purple',edgecolor = 'black')
# Plot the PDF.
xmin, xmax = plt.xlim()
x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 1000)
density = norm.pdf(x, mu_std[0], mu_std[1])
plt.plot(x, density, 'k', linewidth=2)
plt.title("Histogram of IBM returns w.r.t. Normal density (in black)")
plt.show()

Risk minimization

Now, we turn to the computation of the portfolio weights that minimize the variance. First, we need an estimate of the covariance matrix.

get_data = np.array(data,ndmin=2)
returns_universe = np.array(get_data[:,2:12],dtype=float)
Mean_ret = np.array(np.mean(returns_universe,0),ndmin=2,dtype=float)
df_Mean_ret=pd.DataFrame(Mean_ret,columns=data.columns[2:12])
print(df_Mean_ret)

##        MMM       ABT      ATVI      ADBE  ...      AMG       AFL         A       APD
## 0  0.00072  0.000507  0.001401  0.001103  ...  0.00017  0.000631  0.001192  0.000413
## 
## [1 rows x 10 columns]
T = np.size(returns_universe,0)
N = np.size(returns_universe,1)
Sigma_hat = np.zeros([N,N],dtype=float)
for t in range(0,T):
    error = np.transpose(returns_universe[t,:] - Mean_ret)
    Sigma_hat = Sigma_hat + np.dot(error,np.transpose(error))/(T-1)

You could also estimate the covariance matrix using the cov function. It does the same computation as above.

Sigma_hat2 = np.cov(np.transpose(returns_universe),bias=False)
print(np.sum(np.abs(Sigma_hat2-Sigma_hat)))
## 5.2244992186645245e-18

Estimation of the weights

We have an estimation of the covariance matrix. We can plug this estimate into the formula (see the corresponding slides) to get an estimate of the weights.

vect_ones = np.zeros([N,1],dtype = float)+1
inv_Sigma = inv(Sigma_hat)
omega = np.dot(inv_Sigma,vect_ones)/(np.dot(np.dot(np.transpose(vect_ones),inv_Sigma),vect_ones))
print(omega)
